1097901010675216385.text: 8/8 Accurately comparing and allocating trading volumes to each platform is becoming complex. For example, how should we count orders initiated through KyberSwap and settled with Uniswap? What about price aggregation contracts? Does it really matter?

1097901008078995457.text: 7/ The result of comparing volume from individual orders (rather than simultaneous trades) is that Uniswap overtook Bancor on the Ethereum network last week.pic.twitter.com/EOrPrXJvD7

1097901005071634432.text: 6/ The difference between the two reporting methodologies is significant, especially for Bancor! (Pricing data via @nomicsfinance)pic.twitter.com/8Co4zf2rUx

1097901002802507778.text:
5/ In some cases counting individual trades makes sense (e.g. calculating fees).

But, individual orders seem to be the better comparison metric for aggregate data. Otherwise, consider the volumes of an exchange that routes every order through a series of 10 trades. pic.twitter.com/l7jAuzG4DN

1097901000982171648.text:
4/ The basis for this thread is whether volume should be measured for each individual order (comprised of one to many simultaneous trades) or for each and every trade? Maybe somewhere in between?

A hypothetical comparison of the two methods:pic.twitter.com/s2YfGiL911

1097900999749128192.text:
3/ To fulfill orders, both platforms carry out simultaneous, multi-step trades on behalf of their users.

For example, Uniswap carries out two trades to fulfill MKR <> DAI orders:
    1. MKR <> ETH
    2. ETH <> DAI

And so does Bancor:
     1. MKR <> BNT
     2. BNT <> DAI
